---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Chooser — Andrew Shiau"
  description="A skill that renders every design option side by side, in the real system, so you pick by looking."
>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="back"><a href="/">← Index</a></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">04</span></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h1>Chooser</h1></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <p class="dek c1-8" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
      A skill for design decisions with no obvious answer. Instead of describing the
      options in prose, it renders every one for real — in the actual typeface,
      tokens, and grid it will ship in — so you choose by looking.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-8" style="margin-top:calc(var(--unit)*1.5)">
      <p>
        You can't see prose. A byline treatment, a type ramp, a masthead — the
        differences are visual and small, and the only honest way to decide is to
        put the candidates next to each other and use your eyes.
      </p>
      <p>
        I chose this site's layout that way. The demo below is the actual
        chooser I used to pick the experiment grid you're reading now — three
        poster compositions on a 12-column grid, rendered live.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h2>The demo</h2></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <figure class="embed c1-12" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
      <div class="embed-frame embed-tall">
        <iframe src="/demo/index-layouts/" title="A live layout chooser" loading="lazy"></iframe>
      </div>
      <figcaption>
        <a href="/demo/index-layouts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full-screen ↗</a>
        — three index layouts, rendered live, on the real grid
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="facts">
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Form</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          One self-contained HTML page: every option rendered in the real design
          system, labelled, with a one-line rationale. Open it, pick a number.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">The rule</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          The first option is always what's live today, so you read the rest
          against it. A few distinct options beat a dozen near-duplicates.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
